issue.body:
Below are codes of Recvmsg func from x/sys/unix .
```go
// Recvmsg receives a message from a socket using the recvmsg system call. The
// received non-control data will be written to p, and any "out of band"
// control data will be written to oob. The flags are passed to recvmsg.
//
// The results are:
//   - n is the number of non-control data bytes read into p
//   - oobn is the number of control data bytes read into oob; this may be interpreted using [ParseSocketControlMessage]
//   - recvflags is flags returned by recvmsg
//   - from is the address of the sender
//
// If the underlying socket type is not SOCK_DGRAM, a received message
// containing oob data and a single '\0' of non-control data is treated as if
// the message contained only control data, i.e. n will be zero on return.
func Recvmsg(fd int, p, oob []byte, flags int) (n, oobn int, recvflags int, from Sockaddr, err error) {
	var iov [1]Iovec
	if len(p) > 0 {
		iov[0].Base = &p[0]
		iov[0].SetLen(len(p))
	}
	var rsa RawSockaddrAny
	n, oobn, recvflags, err = recvmsgRaw(fd, iov[:], oob, flags, &rsa) //// here recvmsgRaw may return n=-1 and err=EWOULDBLOCK 
	// source address is only specified if the socket is unconnected
	if rsa.Addr.Family != AF_UNSPEC {
		from, err = anyToSockaddr(fd, &rsa) //// later err may be overrided  to nil
	}
	return  //// In this case, it returns n=-1 but err=nil !
}
```

That is possible, right? In this case, unix.Recvmsg returns n=-1 but err=nil !

comment.body:
@thepudds thanks for filing an issue, and if you'd like to send a CL, please feel free!

To put a finer point on it, failing to include a publication barrier here I believe creates the potential for observable out-of-thin-air values, which are forbidden by Go's memory model, even in racy programs.

Here's the "bad" code in question (note that this is using runtime primitives to make a point, but the idea is that the compiler could generate code like this, or the runtime could have code like this (for example in `runtime.growslice`) today):

```go
var gx *[4]int

func allocThenInitialize4Int() {
    x := (*[4]int)(mallocgc(abi.TypeOf([4]int{}), unsafe.Sizeof([4]int{}), false))
    x = [4]int{1, 2, 3, 4}
    // publicationBarrier missing
    gx = x
}

func read() {
    x := gx
    if x != nil {
        println(x[3]) // can read out-of-thin-air value on architectures with weak memory models
    }
}

func main() {
    go read()
    allocThenInitialize4Int()
}
```

CC @randall77 who might have more to say about this issue.

@junpuf Thanks for your work! I think it is in good shape, with some minor comments:

* There should be some checks in case `FINAL_BASE_IMAGE` is overridden to use a newer version. For example, only do the debianization if `"$(lsb_release -c -s)" == "jammy"`?
* #30443 could be merged first. Although your changes are orthogonal, there might be potential merge conflicts.

@vault-thirteen You can report security issues confidentially as described at https://go.dev/doc/security/policy.

If there is an actual problem here the Go team will reopen this issue or open a new one.

Thanks.

