issue.body:
The following 4 lines can have different results:

```js
// Assuming that both a and b are unused.
const [a, b] = unknown;
const [ , ,] = unknown;
const [] = unknown;
unknown;
```

It's not hard to optimize the first line into any of these 3 lines. The problem is how to design the options.

**Input:**
```js
function Main() {
  const p = {};
  p.__proto__ = p.__proto__ || {};
  p.__proto__.a = 124;
  const m = Math.random(10);
  return m;
}


Main();

console.log(window.a);
```

**Expected Output:**

Include all statements.

**Actual Output:**

It seems that objects created by literals do not have a prototype chain, and references to global objects are automatically retained.

```js
function Main() {
  const __unused_4577 = Math.random(10);
  return;
}
Main();
console.log(window.a);
```

